{
  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces Confidence-Aware Adaptive Contrastive Decoding (CAACD), a novel decoding framework for Neural Machine Translation that dynamically adjusts the strength of Contrastive Decoding based on a real-time confidence signal derived from the expert model’s internal representations. While traditional Contrastive Decoding applies a uniform or heuristically scaled penalty to suppress hallucinations by contrasting the full model against an encoder-diminished counterpart, it risks degrading high-fidelity translations when applied too aggressively. CAACD addresses this limitation by introducing a learnable, lightweight confidence estimator module that operates during autoregressive generation to assess the model's certainty in each predicted token. This estimator leverages multiple uncertainty indicators—including token-level entropy, attention variance across decoder layers, encoder-decoder representation similarity (via cosine distance in hidden states), and predictive stability under minor input perturbations—to produce a normalized confidence score. This score is then used to gate the intensity of the contrastive term in the decoding objective: when confidence is high, CD strength is reduced to preserve fluent and accurate translations; when confidence drops below a learned threshold, CD is amplified to suppress potential hallucinations. Crucially, the confidence estimator is trained on a synthetic dataset enriched with human-annotated hallucination patterns (inspired by Paper 3’s annotation framework), using supervision from both automatic discrepancy metrics (e.g., COMET, BERTScore) and glass-box uncertainty labels. The system is designed to operate entirely at inference time without requiring gold references, making it suitable for real-world deployment. By adaptively modulating CD strength, CAACD achieves a superior balance between faithfulness and fluency, minimizing unnecessary suppression of correct content while effectively mitigating hallucinations. This approach advances beyond static or scalar-gated CD methods (e.g., max-probability gating in Paper 1) and diverges from post-hoc search modifications like FECS (Paper 2) by embedding adaptivity directly into the contrastive mechanism. Potential impact includes improved reliability in multilingual NMT systems, particularly for low-resource languages where hallucinations are more prevalent and harder to detect. Furthermore, the modular design allows integration with various architectures (Transformer, Mamba, etc.) and tasks beyond translation, such as summarization and dialogue.",
  "Title": "Confidence-Aware Adaptive Contrastive Decoding for Dynamic Hallucination Mitigation in Neural Machine Translation",
