  "Idea": "The proposed idea introduces Contextual Fidelity Modulation (CFM), a novel, architecture-aware extension of Contrastive Decoding that dynamically adjusts the intensity of contrastive supervision not just globally per token, but locally across attention heads and decoder layers based on learned contextual vulnerability signals. Unlike prior methods that apply uniform or scalar-gated penalties (e.g., Paper 1’s max-probability weighting) or modify search trajectories post-hoc (e.g., FECS in Paper 2), CFM embeds a lightweight fidelity controller within the decoding loop that monitors the stability and alignment of cross-attention distributions relative to the source encoding. Specifically, at each autoregressive step, the controller computes a multi-dimensional fidelity score by analyzing: (1) cross-attention entropy across decoder layers, (2) deviation from expected attention centrality (measured via KL-divergence from a canonical attention profile trained on non-hallucinated pairs), (3) gradient sensitivity of output logits to encoder input dropout, and (4) consistency of top-k attended source tokens under minor embedding perturbations. These features feed into a small transformer-based modulator that outputs a tensor of contrastive weights γ_t ∈ ℝ^(L×H), where L is the number of decoder layers and H is the number of attention heads. This allows CFM to amplify contrastive pressure selectively in attention heads that exhibit unstable or incoherent source grounding—often precursors to hallucination—while leaving well-aligned heads untouched. The overall decoding objective becomes a head-specific weighted sum: log P(y_t|y_<t, x) + Σ_{l,h} γ_t[l,h] ⋅ (log P_full − log P_diminished)[l,h], ensuring that suppression is targeted rather than blanket. The fidelity controller is pre-trained on a synthetic dataset generated by inducing realistic hallucinations through controlled source omissions, synonym substitutions, and syntactic inversions, with labels derived from