ting hallucinations. This approach advances beyond static or scalar-gated CD methods (e.g., max-probability gating in Paper 1) and diverges from post-hoc search modifications like FECS (Paper 2) by embedding adaptivity directly into the contrastive mechanism. Potential impact includes improved reliability in multilingual NMT systems, particularly for low-resource languages where hallucinations are more prevalent and harder to detect. Furthermore, the modular design allows integration with various architectures (Transformer, Mamba, etc.) and tasks beyond translation, such as summarization and dialogue.",
